For the top 14: 

Taking a stack of 14 supplements requires a structured approach to ensure you aren't putting undue stress on your kidneys or liver, and to maximize absorption. While most of these are generally safe, combining them all at once can be counterproductive due to competition for absorption and metabolic load.

The "Kidney Overload" Question
The term "kidney overload" is usually a concern when the kidneys have to process excessive amounts of protein or specific minerals.

Amino Acid Load: You have four supplements that are protein-based or amino acids (Glycine, Serine, Tryptophan, Collagen). While the kidneys easily filter these in healthy individuals, taking massive doses all at once increases the production of urea, which requires high water intake to flush.

Oxalates: Matcha is high in oxalates, which can contribute to kidney stones if you are predisposed and not drinking enough water.

Potassium: This is the most "dangerous" item on your list if mismanaged. Excessive potassium can lead to hyperkalemia (irregular heart rhythm). Ensure you are not exceeding the Recommended Dietary Allowance (RDA) unless under medical supervision.

Recommended 24-Hour Regimen
To minimize "overload" and ensure these supplements work together, I would divide them into three distinct windows:

Window 1: Morning (Energy & Metabolism)
NMN: Best taken on an empty stomach in the morning to support NAD+ levels.

Matcha: Provides caffeine and L-theanine for focused energy.

Creatine: 3–5g daily. It is "foundational" and can be taken anytime, but morning helps with consistency. Crucial: Drink an extra 8–12 oz of water with this.

Collagen: Often taken in the morning coffee or a shake. It provides a broad spectrum of amino acids.

Potassium: Take this with your first meal. Never take concentrated potassium on an empty stomach, as it can irritate the GI lining.

Window 2: With Meals (Digestion & Support)
Apple Cider Vinegar (ACV): Take 10–20 minutes before your largest meal (diluted in water) to help with glycemic control.

Bile Salts: Take with a meal that contains fat. If the meal is low-fat, skip the bile salts.

L-Reuteri: Probiotics generally survive better when taken with a meal or shortly after.

Devil’s Claw: This herbal anti-inflammatory can increase stomach acid, so it is best taken with food to prevent irritation.

Hawthorn: Typically taken twice daily (morning/afternoon).

Window 3: Evening (Recovery & Sleep)
Glycine & Tryptophan: These are highly effective for sleep quality. Glycine helps lower core body temperature, and Tryptophan is a precursor to melatonin.

Serine: Works synergistically with Glycine for cognitive and nervous system support.

D-Mannose: Often taken before bed so it can sit in the bladder overnight to prevent bacterial adhesion.

Critical Safety Checks
The "Serotonin" Warning: If you take any prescription antidepressants (SSRIs/MAOIs), Tryptophan is a major red flag. Combining them can lead to Serotonin Syndrome, which is a medical emergency.

Heart/Blood Pressure: Both Hawthorn and Devil’s Claw can influence blood pressure and heart rate. If you are already on blood pressure medication, these could cause your levels to drop too low.

Stomach Health: If you have a history of stomach ulcers, be very cautious with Devil’s Claw and ACV, as both can increase acidity.

How Long Can You Take These?
Foundationals (Indefinite): Glycine, Creatine, Collagen, L-Reuteri, NMN, and D-Mannose are generally safe for long-term daily use (years).

Herbal Cycling (8–12 Weeks): It is a common practice to cycle herbs like Devil's Claw and Hawthorn. Taking them for 8–12 weeks followed by a 2-week break helps prevent "tachyphylaxis" (where the body becomes desensitized to the herb) and reduces the risk of rare cumulative side effects.
